06485nam a22008295i 9781685850036DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222000cou    fo  d z      eng d  a97816858500367 a10.1515/97816858500362doi  a(DE-B1597)623174  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acoucUS-CO 7aPOL0340002bisacsh00aFemale "Circumcision" in Africa :bCulture, Controversy, Change /ced. by Ylva Hernlund, Bettina Shell-Duncan. 1aBoulder : bLynne Rienner Publishers, c[2022] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDirections in Applied Anthropology: Adaptations and Innovations00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1 Female “Circumcision” in Africa: Dimensions of the Practice and Debates -- t2 Is Female “Circumcision” a Maladaptive Cultural Pattern? -- t3 To Marry and Bear Children? The Demographic Consequences of Infibulation in Sudan -- t4 Female “Circumcision” Among the Yoruba of Southwestern Nigeria: The Beginning of Change -- t5 Female Genital Cutting in Nigeria: Views of Nigerian Doctors on the Medicalization Debate -- t6 Women Without Choices: The Debate over Medicalization of Female Genital Cutting and Its Impact on a Northern Kenyan Community -- t7 “Ngaitana (I Will Circumcise Myself)”: Lessons from Colonial Campaigns to Ban Excision in Meru, Kenya -- t8 Revisiting Feminist Discourses on Infibulation: Responses from Sudanese Feminists -- t9 Adopting Female “Circumcision” in Southern Chad: The Experience of Myabé -- t10 Handing over the Knife: Numu Women and the Campaign Against Excision in Mali -- t11 Becoming a Muslim, Becoming a Person: Female “Circumcision,” Religious Identity, and Personhood in Guinea-Bissau -- t12 Cutting Without Ritual and Ritual Without Cutting: Female “Circumcision” and the Re-ritualization of Initiation in the Gambia -- t13 Female Genital Cutting: The Beginning of the End -- t14 Rites and Wrongs: An Insider/ Outsider Reflects on Power and Excision -- tBibliography -- tThe Contributors -- tIndex -- tAbout the Book0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThough the issue of female genital cutting, or "circumcision," has become a nexus for debates on cultural relativism, human rights, patriarchal oppression, racism, and Western imperialism, the literature has been separated by diverse fields of study. In contrast, this volume brings together contributors from anthropology, public health, political science, demography, history, and epidemiology to critically examine current debates and initiatives, and to explore the role that scholars can and should—or should not—play in approaching the issue. Case studies from nine African countries where female genital cutting (FGC) is traditionally and currently performed evaluate the impact of international efforts to eliminate the practice. A focus on local reactions to external involvement underscores that the myriad programs fashioned to effect changes in FGC ritual and procedure must be initiated and supported by indigenous communities if they are to be lasting and effective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Peace.2bisacsh1 aAbusharaf, Rogaia Mustafa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAhmadu, Fuambai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAuko Muruli, Leunita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalk, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldwell, John C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldwell, Pat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGosselin, Claudie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r